to sum it up:<br>
<br>
Japanese /r/ is probably a retroflex [l] )(lateral approximant... uh... so it's an approximant too... well... but a lateral one... the pure approximants are somewhat less consonant-like, e.g. swiss german and dutch &lt;w&gt; is a bit like a mix between [w] and [v] - i guess... ) (lots of retroflex sounds in some indian langauges, btw, and some in some of the  sardinian and southern italian idioms... well, retroflex [d] in sardinian, in any case; it actually comes from retroflex [l] that developed from Latin [ll]; i.e. long [l:]<br>
<br>
Italian and Spanish /r/ is an alveolar trill<br>
<br>
BBC English /r/ is an alveolar approximant; General American /r/ is probably a retroflex approximant (Daniel Jones's phonology said so, if i remember correctly)<br>
<br>
BBC English /l/ has two allophones, namely the so-called clear /l/ as in LOVE (it's a lateral approximant) and the velarized /l/ in BILL that sounds a bit like /w/. In General American there is only the velarized /l/ that however sounds less like /w/, probably because there would be danger of confusing it with initial /w/ as in WATER. <br>
<br>
D and B ? i didnt get it... well, both /d/ (as in DEAN) and /b/ (as in BOOK) are voiced plsoives... <br>
